Sub-Saharan African Stocks Report: Access Bank, KenolKobil

-- B y   S t e p h e n   G u n n i o n
-- 
2011-09-26T16:03:14Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-09-26/sub-saharan-african-stocks-report-kenolkobil-kenya-power-move.html
Kenya ’s All-Share Index declined
for a sixth day, falling 1.3 percent to 59.44 by the 3 p.m.
close in Nairobi, the capital. The Nigerian Stock Exchange All-
Share Index closed at its lowest since April 2009, dropping 0.1
percent to 20,175.54 by the 2:30 p.m. close in Lagos, according
to a statement on the bourse’s  website . Namibia’s FTSE/ Namibia
Overall Index (FTN098)  retreated for a fourth day, slipping 0.7 percent
to 763.85 by the 4 p.m. close in Windhoek. In Mauritius, the
SEMDEX Index fell for a third day, slipping 0.4 percent to
1,850.11 by the 1:30 p.m. close in  Port Louis . The Ghana Stock
Exchange Composite Index slid 0.6 percent to 1,101.07 by the 3
p.m. close in Accra.  The following shares rose or fell in sub-Saharan  Africa ,
excluding  South Africa . Stock symbols are in parentheses.  Access Bank Plc (ACCESS)  , a Nigerian lender, fell to the
lowest since September 2009, dropping 26 kobo, or 5 percent, to
4.95 naira. Shareholders of Intercontinental Bank Plc of  Nigeria 
approved the acquisition of the lender by Lagos-based Access
Bank.  KenolKobil Ltd. (KNOC KN), a fuel retailer with operations
in nine Africa countries, declined 15 cents, or 1.5 percent, to
10 shillings. Oil hovered near a seven-week low of $80 a barrel
after new home sales in the U.S. dropped to the weakest in six
months, adding to concern about demand in the slowing economy.  Kenya Power Ltd. (KPLL KN), the East African nation’s sole
electricity distributor, fell 15 cents, or 0.8 percent, to 18.85
shillings, the lowest since Sept. 15. The company is in a
dispute with Kenya’s energy industry regulator over a new tariff
plan that will see industrial consumers paying less for
electricity during off-peak hours, the  Business Daily newspaper
reported .  To contact the reporter on this story:
Stephen Gunnion in Johannesburg at 
